```javascript

starknet.provider.callContract( ... )

Author: janek26
Content:
Hey guys! Had to catch some sleep

As there are no EOAs in StarkNet Signers are the only way to interact (write) with the blockchain, instances can sign data, verify those signatures and commit given transactions to a given address, which need to implement a wallet-contract interface as defined by openzeppelin. The 2 implementations for that are openzeppelins account contract and argents account contract afaik.

**Please note you wont be able to make transactions without going through a wallet contract in the future, as revealed yesterday in the community call**
While you can still write to the blockchain directly right now, this will change in the future, so it's better to be prepared today. (Contract deployment wont be effected by this change for now)

If you want the most basic signer (should work in node too) you need to generate a keypair, deploy a account contract, and initialize a Signer with that keypair and wallet contract address.

Author: odinfree
Content:
Hi Fren, 
What's the difference between StarkEx and StarkNet?
StarkEx is a standalone system for exchanges that uses the STARK proof system in order to provide scalability for the exchanges using it. See above for a list of exchanges already using StarkEx in production on Ethereum mainnet.
See https://starkware.co/product/starkex/

StarkNet is a general-purpose system, where you can write and deploy your own contracts, interact with other contracts, and so on, just like Ethereum.
See https://starkware.co/product/starknet/

Have a good day
Oli

Author: 0xjon#0981
Content:
Something like this should work

```
import * as starknet from "starknet"

const pk = "0xPRIVATE_KEY_HERE"
const yourAccountAddress = "0xACCOUNT_CONTRACT_ADDRESS"

const yourKeyPair = starknet.ec.ec.keyFromPrivate(pk, "hex");
const signer = new starknet.Signer(starknet.defaultProvider, yourAccountAddress, yourKeyPair);
```

Author: Henri#6408
Content:
hey, I'll let you do your homework if you think StarkNet is not a good fit :-). 
I'll say that no other L2 is decentralized at the moment; and none of them is as secure and production ready as we are. We are by and large the leader on all fronts. Look beyong medium posts and twitter announcements.
I simply am giving you the facts as they are for now: yes, this is still being developed. Yes, it will take some time. Yes, it will kick ass when it's fully shipped.
September is a decent deadline though, there will be plenty of functionnalities shipped at that time.
Does that answer your question?

As I have seen the code, there are 2 approaches to call and invoke
- by wrapping into a `Contract` class, this gives a power to do a parameter validation and calldata parsing, (the example is lack of this tho)
- by calling `defaultProvider.invokeFunction` `defaultProvider.callContract`, this approach doesn't need ABI, just pass a contract address and you are good to go (similar to the README example, this one would call a gateway and feeder gateway api directly (via axios call, it's that simple
.
The question is **which one is the better practice the first or second** implementation

Author: MilGard#2688
Content:
We are currently working on new documentation for starknet.js.

There are couple of ways you can invoke or call function.
The easiest is call it directly on the contract.

`const response = contract.balanceOf(wallet)`
or 
`cont response = contract.invoke('balanceOf', [wallet])`

also arguments can be numbers, array of numbers, objects or array of object. That's why we changed to `any`

We made Contract interface to be similar to ethers.js.

Hope this helps

Content:
@here **New Release of the Starknet.js 3.9.0**
- provider expanded with getTransactionTrace
- Support for the estimate fee
- Automatic calculation of max fee if max fee not provided
- Options object fix when invoking  functions
- Account constructor takes a KeyPair or a Signer as parameter
- pending block is now considered as successful

https://github.com/0xs34n/starknet.js/releases/tag/v3.9.0

Author: grillo.eth
Content:
Hello everyone, I'm trying to verify a signed message on my server, and I think I'm almost there, but something is missing:
1) I'm using ArgentX on the frontend to sign a message via signMessage() and obtain a signature.
2) I'm able to call hashMessage() to obtain the message hash, and later verify it via a contract call to is_valid_signature().
This works great!

My problem is that, I could either:
A. Send the message and the signature to the server. In this case, I would need to recalculate the hash and verify it via is_valid_signature(). But I don't know how to recalculate the hash server-side, and it seems like hashMessage() returns a different hash for every different signer.
B. Send the message, the hash and the signature to the server. In this case, I would be able to verify that the hash is valid, but I would still need a way to verify that the hash corresponds to the message.

Anyone has any tip to guide me to a solution? Thanks!

Author: Antun | ShardLabs#0568
Content: It works with the CRA as well. There is a great library with React hooks https://github.com/apibara/starknet-react. One pain point for the community was loading of the compiled artifacts on the client side and Next.js has a useful workaround for that with the use of API routes. This is because compiled JSON file needs to parsed with BigNumber json parse utility, another workaround would be to create a Webpack loader that uses BigNumber json parse üññ

Content:
I am having an issue calling a contract. When trying to call the contract through starknetjs, the request made is https://alpha4.starknet.io/feeder_gateway/call_contract?blockNumber=pending which leads to an error

There is a reported bug in voyager that contracts deployed in factories get stuck in pending, so I'm wondering whether this has a knock on effect on starknetjs requests?

Making the request to the contract directly through feeder_gateway works: `https://alpha4.starknet.io/feeder_gateway/call_contract`
body:
```
{
    "contract_address": "0x03053e2e251cb67e652baf3a3ff091f807bfdc1f01ee21ef64180559bc0ee739",
    "entry_point_selector": "0x361458367e696363fbcc70777d07ebbd2394e89fd0adcaf147faccd1d294d60",
    "calldata": [],
    "signature": []
}
```
Contract stuck in pending for reference: https://goerli.voyager.online/contract/0x03053e2e251cb67e652baf3a3ff091f807bfdc1f01ee21ef64180559bc0ee739

Author: lazarmitic
Content:
this is an example 
```
return this.provider.getEvents({
      address: this.contract.address, // address of the contract that emitted the event
      page_size: 1024, // page size (number of events per query)
      fromBlock: 282899, // start block
      toBlock: 295081, // end block
      keys: [], // you can use this to filter events - if you pass empty array it will fetch all events from the contract
      page_number: 0, // page you want to fetch 
    });
```

Author: gregoryguillou
Content:
Hello, Starknet-js 3.19 is not compatible with 3.18 and the version before. My understanding is that it would better have been called `4.0.0-alpha`. If your rule for starknet in your package.json is ^3.x with x<=18, you might get bite. The move to the `latest` tag to v4.4.2 should not have impacted your code.... except that it has.

If you run npm install from scratch, you get the 3.19 (19 > 18) and not 3.18... if you do that, your package will (likely) be broken. A quick fix is to block the version (if you are running starknet-js 3) to 3.18.2.

But I am guessing everybody should be running 4.4 already now.

Author: gregoryguillou
Content:
Hi,
`invoke` like in `invokeFunction` on the Provider ? 
1- There is nothing wrong about using strings. You should use string as you can see from the type that is used in the `invokeFunction` here https://github.com/0xs34n/starknet.js/blob/b4785793ea912dc8562de4c69b0dcbda4358e144/src/types/lib.ts#L20
2- The correct way to proceed (assuming you want to write to the blockchain) would be (1) create an account and (2) `execute` a contract function from that account. But before that, did you connect to your wallet? How did you do that? The way it works is the transaction needs to be signed by the user and the easiest way is definitely to ask your wallet to sign it for you.
3- You also need to check the version of starknet-js. What version are you using?
4- If you are stuck, there are several things you could do: (1) find an example and make sure it works; (2) explain where you are stuck (3) provide the code extract and the exact error message you get in details

Author: 0xdarlington
Content:
3 days ago, i was looking to build a UI for my Cairo contract with Starknet.js. 

Took some days of tirelessly searching through Discord channels, to come up with a working UI. So i wrote an in-depth guide to help you get started with Starknet.js easily.

For a full walk through, check out my article on medium here:

Content: and how can I get `transaction.classHash`.

Author: gregoryguillou
Content:
You need to have declared the class contract on the blockchain 1st. The process is this one with the new DEPLOY_CONTRACT syscall:
1. we assume the account class is in the blockchain
2. You need to compute the contract hash
3. You need to send ETH to that address
4. You call that function. 

Why do you do that with starknet.js? Most cases, you would rely on an higher level like the Hardhat plugin for starknet, the starknet CLI, caigo (my case) or some tools that does it for you, like Argent-X or Braavos.

hi! üëã 
You are maybe aware that soon StarkNet will not allow free deployments of Accounts. 
That is why we modified and updated our workshop repo, which you can check out on how to adapt your flow: https://github.com/0xs34n/starknet.js-workshop

For an example that uses the Argent Account contract check out: https://github.com/0xs34n/starknet.js-account
For the theory check out this guide: https://starkware.notion.site/Deploy-a-contract-and-an-account-on-StarkNet-ed2fd13301d2414e8223bb72bb90e386
NOTE: starknet.js guides are not yet up to date with these changes, but they will be very soon

Author: robertkodra
Content: Is it possible to receive a value from a cairo external function? For example if I use the `account.execute` function, I' m receiving the `code` and `transaction_hash`. However the cairo function also returns a set of values. How could I get those?e

Author: phil26
Content: Starknet.js documentation includes guides. This one could help you : https://www.starknetjs.com/docs/guides/interact

Author: phil26
Content:
As you can see in this guide, the `account.execute `method is one way : DAPP --> smart-contract. Only the command `contract.call` works in the Smart-contract --> DAPP way.
You account must have a logic in accordance. For example, ArgentX accounts send back the answers via events.

Starknet.js do not accept mnemonic phrase as input. If it's an ArgentX or Braavos account, import the account in the wallet with the  mnemonic phrase, then export the privkey from the wallet. With this private key, you can work with Starknet.js.

Author: phil26
Content:
Hello, Blockchains are not *query* friendly. At best, you can read the content of a block.
You need a middleware that has database capability. Several ways :
- use an explorer. Some have an API to query the blockchain (for example : https://starkscan.readme.io/reference/starkscan-api-introduction)
- use a local or remote node that includes querying capabilities.
Personally, I have an old miniPC (8W of electrical power, 2 Tb SSD) with a pathfinder node running H24.  I can connect my DAPP to my node by this way :
https://www.starknetjs.com/docs/next/guides/connect_network#connect-your-dapp-to-a-starknet-node
and I can query the historical of events this way :
https://www.starknetjs.com/docs/next/guides/connect_network#specific-rpc-methods

Author: phil26

Author: phil26
Content:
In Starknet, ETH token is an ERC20 as any other (not the case in Ethereum).

Author: loouo
Content: I tried to search for two addresses on starkscan, looks like the two addresses are the same one. Just don't know where the 0 is inserted after 0x for the address displayed in ArgentX

Author: phil26
Content:
It's not really a starknet.js problem. It's rather a problem of understanding of Starknet blockchain and cryptography.
PrivateKey is a secret that has to be stored outside of the network, and is used as a paswword.
Public key is stored in the account contract in the network, and is used by the account to verify that you own the private key.

Author: phil26
Content: The address is the location of the account contract in the network.

Author: phil26
Content: left zeros are not significant in a number (in any base : binary,decimal,octal, hexa, ....)

Author: phil26
Content: In hexa, some devs uses the minimum of digits, some others wants an even number of digits. It explains your problem. These address formats can be easily converted.

Author: dohoiwqel
Content: guys, how can i get address from my keyPair ?

Author: phil26
Content:
Hello,
With only the keyPair, you can't!
But if you know the Salt value used at the creation of the account, you can calculate the account address.
Generally, the Salt is equal to the pubKey.
Here an example of calculation, pubKey as Salt :
```typescript
const OZaccountConstructorCallData = stark.compileCalldata({ publicKey: starkKeyPub });
    const OZcontractAddress = hash.calculateContractAddressFromHash( starkKeyPub,decClassHash, OZaccountConstructorCallData, 0);
```

Author: phil26
Content:
In fact, you can't use a compressedContract to declare. SierraContractClass is for Cairo 1 compressed contract.
You have to use Cairo 1 compiled contract : CompiledSierra.
An issue has been created yesterday on this subject : https://github.com/0xs34n/starknet.js/issues/588
As the problem is in the communication protocol with the sequencer/node, it will not be solved soon.
If your sierra contract contains something like this, it's a compiled contract :
```
    "program": {
        "attributes": [],
        "builtins": [
            "pedersen",
            "range_check"
        ],
        "compiler_version": "0.10.3",
        "data": [
            "0x20780017fff7ffd",
            "0x4",
            "0x400780017fff7ffd",
            "0x1",
            "0x208b7fff7fff7ffe",
            "0x480680017fff8000",
            "0x4c69627261727943616c6c",
            "0x400280007ff97fff",
            "0x400380017ff97ffa",
            "0x400380027ff97ffb",
            "0x400380037ff97ffc",
            "0x400380047ff97ffd",
            "0x482680017ff98000",
```

Author: phil26
Content:
If your sierra contract contains this, it's a compressed contract :
```
"program": "
```

How have you calculated the compiledClassHash?

Here is an example of Declare & deploy, using the compiled sierra  file and the casm file : https://github.com/PhilippeR26/starknet.js-workshop-typescript/blob/main/src/scripts/cairo11-devnet/4b.declareAndDeployHello.ts

Author: phil26

Author: phil26
Content:
So,
You will find explanation here : https://docs.starknet.io/documentation/getting_started/cli/#simulate-transaction
Item 2 is the contract address
Item 3 is selector, obtained with `hash.getSelectorFromName('approve')`
Item 5&6 are number of parameters.
Then the parameters : one address, and an uint256 (2 felts)
Other values are separators or are useless .

There is no method provided by starknet.js to go back to the initial names and values of the parameters.
Theoretically, with the ABI, it should be possible.

Author: phil26
Content:
The proxy is a deployed contract (with an address), containing the code to update and to send/receive/transfer requests. It contains also the storage of the implementation code (including the class hash of the implementation).
The implementation is just a declared class hash, including only the code, without deployment address, without storage.

Author: phil26
Content:
üì¢ 
Today situation (v5.6.0) :
u8, u16, u32, usize, u64, u128, ContractAddress are working.
u256 should not be used.
Tuple, struct and array (made of predefined type) are working.
More complex object should not be used.

So, to call/invoke smart-contract using compatible types, just use :
```typescript
const res1 = await myTestContract.test_tup_out(100, 200, 150);
```

Author: phil26
phil26
Content:
v4 to V5 is a major change, with many impacts.
For the provider, V5 syntax :
import constants, then
```typescript
const provider = new Provider({ sequencer: { network: constants.NetworkName.SN_GOERLI } });
```

The normal way is to use account.execute, that will handle everything automatically in one step.

Content: Hello,i have a question,if i have account on braavos wallet how to deploy this account using starknet.js?

Author: phil26
Content:
Hello,
If you are working just with a node.js script, you have just to use an Account object, created with the address and the private key of the Braavos (or ArgentX) account.
If you are developing  a DAPP, you have to use one library : get-starknet.js . It's developed by ArgentX & Braavos. Today, it's compatible only with Starknet.js v4.

Author: golang_
Content: So I need the private key for every transaction I get?

Author: phil26
Content:
You provide the private key when you create the Account object ; then starknet.js is using automatically the private key at each transaction that needs fees or the proof that you own the account.
See : https://www.starknetjs.com/docs/next/guides/connect_account#-connect-an-existing-account-in-any-network

Author: augustbleeds
Content: What is the difference between compiled class hash and class hash?

Author: phil26
Content:
You have problems with Uint256.
Uint256 can be created with uint256.bnTouint256(num).
Then it has to be transformed to 2 felts to be understood by Starknet. In some cases, you have to do it manually, in others it's automatic.
These 2 guides will help you :
https://www.starknetjs.com/docs/guides/define_call_message <-- read very carefully this one ; all is super important 
https://www.starknetjs.com/docs/guides/use_ERC20

Author: phil26
Content:
- compiled class hash
- class hash
- compressed clash hash
What a mess!!!üëπ

Author: phil26
Content: class hash is a number, representing a class program.

Author: phil26
Content:
compiled class is the .sierra file from the compilation.
compressed class is  the compiled class, with the .program part compressed with gzip.

Author: augustbleeds
Content: ^ so a contract is uniquely identified by its class hash. So why are there 2 forms if it's unique?

Author: phil26
Content:
contract !== class hash
a contract is identified by its address.
A class is identified by its class hash.

const starkKeyPairAX = ec.starkCurve.getStarkKey(privateKey);

?

Author: phil26
Content:
Hello,
Starknet public key and full public key are different (in fact the first one is part of the second).
In your case, you need the Starknet public key, and the code is different for V5.

Author: phil26
Content:
For devs of DAPPS, Next.js just released the v13.4.1.
This version is a significant improvement for starknet.js users.
You can now  exchange easily data between server and front-end of your DAPP, all in Javascript/typescript. In fact Next.js become a framework very similar to PHP, but all in JS/typescript.

If I have some free time (and of course if the community find it interesting), I will create a demo DAPP, explaining how to use these new functionalities, for example to create an airdrop DAPP, with the list of airdrop addresses in the back-end.

For a mint, the smart-contract needs the proof that you have the private key. Invoke do not provide this proof in most cases. You have to use account.execute or use meta-class with contract connected to an account. You can see an example of mint in my tuto here : https://github.com/PhilippeR26/starknet.js-workshop-typescript/blob/8eda6ef3614a7907e8bf7b046eb8342ff8dc911a/src/starknet_jsExistingAccount.ts#L57

Content: Starknet.js will perform a full check of conformity with the ABI of the contract, reorder the objects properties if necessary, stop if something is wrong or missing, remove not requested  properties, convert everything to Starknet format :

Author: phil26

Content: Now, Starknet.js will alert earlier of errors in your parameters  (with human comprehensible words), before call to Starknet. So, no more incomprehensible Starknet messages due to parameters construction.

Author: phil26
Content:
Hello,
People are using blockchain explorer, like etherscan, voyager or starkscan. They have the feeling that a blockchain is a SQL database that can be queried in all imaginable ways.
In reality, a blockchain is the worst architecture if you want to query its content (it has other advantages that explains its success).
You can't perform such query directly with Starknet.js. You can only have data from a particular block, not from the whole block-chain.
Blockchain explorers are in real time extracting  the new blocks, and copy them in their local SQL type database. Then you can consult and query this database ; you have just to trust that this database is really a perfect copy of the blockchain.

Author: phil26
Content:
Blockchain explorers are proposing API to access and query their database. With these API, you can query in all ways the blockchain content, in your Javascript/Typescript code.
For example, starkscan sells access to their database. Their recommended solution is about 500 US$ per month : https://starkscan.co/api-info

Author: Zz#5399
Content: dumb question but how do I get the RpcProvider nodeURL for staknet.js?

Author: phil26
Content:
Each node has its own URL.
I have my own mainnet node at home. I can access it internally with `http://192.168.1.99:9545`
Some companies are proposing access to their node. It's free for a very limited access, and you have to pay for a larger access. For example, if you have  an access to Alchemy (you have obtained from them an API key), you can connect your provider object with :
```typescript
const provider = new RpcProvider({ nodeUrl: 'https://starknet-mainnet.g.alchemy.com/v2/' + alchemyKey });
```
In a not so far future, nodes will be the only access to Starknet.

Author: phil26
Content:
For Cairo 0, you need to use : cairo.uint256(10)
For Cairo 1, you can use a BigNumberish type.

This is an extract of the not yet official v5 guide :
```typescript
await myContract0.my_function({low: 100, high: 0}) // Cairo 0 & 1 contract
await myContract1.my_function(cairo.uint256(100)) // Cairo 0 & 1 contract
await myContract2.my_function(12345678, "13456789765", "0xe23a40b543f", 1534566734334n) // Cairo 1 contract
```

Author: apoorvsadana
Content: what does 0x100000000000000000000000000000001 mean in the version? Shouldn't it be 0x0 or 0x1?

Author: phil26
Content:
Hello,
in the version? the version of what?

Author: apoorvsadana
Content: inside `starknet.stark.compileCalldata`

Author: apoorvsadana
Content:
also can you help me understand what some elements of the calldata mean here (this is the call data for transfer on ethereum)

```
[
    "0x1", // calldata length
    "0x40e59c2c182a58fb0a74349bfa4769cbbcba32547591dd3fb1def8623997d01", // eth address
    "0x83afd3f4caedc6eebf44246fe54e38c95e3179a5ec9ea81740eca5b482d12e", // transder selector
    "0x0", // ??
    "0x3", // ??
    "0x3", // number of arguments
    "0x40e59c2c182a58fb0a74349bfa4769cbbcba32547591dd3fb1def8623997d00", // recepient
    "0xf4240", // uint low
    "0x0" // uint high
]
```

what are the `??` above?

Author: phil26
Content:
Well, in v4.22, stark.compileCalldata output is
```typescript
export function compileCalldata(args: RawArgs): Calldata
```
and `Calldata` is  an array of strings. It's not an object with a `version` key.
So, I do not see the relationship between the `stark.compileCalldata` command and a `version` number.

Author: phil26
Content: Could you show the code that generates this result?

Author: apoorvsadana
Content: sorry, my bad, it was `account.execute`

Author: apoorvsadana
phil26
Content:
OK. 
And how have you have read this `version`? Which command?

Author: apoorvsadana
Content: I inspected the http call which was made because of account.execute

Author: apoorvsadana
Content: I saw it over there

Author: apoorvsadana
Content: version in the bottom right

Author: phil26
Content:
Now I understand.
It's a request to estimate the fee of a transaction.
In Starknet, it exists a version for each type of transaction (the official documentation of Starknet is explaining this in detail : https://docs.starknet.io/documentation/architecture_and_concepts/Blocks/transactions/ ).
And this number is different is it's for a query (fee estimation). So version is a complicated subject and is managed automatically by Starknet.js.
This number `0x100000000000000000000000000000001` is the version for a fee estimation of an Invoke.
The detail in the source code of Starknet : https://github.com/starkware-libs/cairo-lang/blob/00ee90123c0bbaffe13dd05a79d2d57b0cb747be/src/starkware/starknet/definitions/constants.py#LL64C9-L64C9

Author: apoorvsadana
Content: I see, so fee estimation has a separate version calculation happening as compared to invoke? and the invoke transaction will have verson as 0x1 only?

Author: apoorvsadana
Content: also, can you help me with what 0x0,0x3 (4th and 5th element of the calldata array) mean in the image above

Author: phil26
Content: Correct.

Author: phil26
Content:
This format has been defined by OpenZeppelin for multicalls : https://github.com/OpenZeppelin/cairo-contracts/blob/4dd04250c55ae8a5bbcb72663c989bb204e8d998/src/openzeppelin/account/library.cairo#L52-L57.
It's `data_offset` and `data_len` ; they are automatically calculated by Starknet.js.
A Starknet.js user do not have to care about these ultra low level data.

Author: 0xandee
Content:
hi, I want to turn this very large number (tokenId):

`1194802964755575003308143629224781921723543461734571264761272012043974606848` 

into a low - high struct format as:

```
    "tokenId.high": "3511210338539747749481185164260461953",
    "tokenId.low": "299188519126458552355543310660827873280"
```

How can I do that using starknet.js? Thanks in advance!

Author: phil26
Content:
Hello,
Easy with starknet.js v5 :
```typescript
const tokenId = cairo.uint256("1194802964755575003308143629224781921723543461734571264761272012043974606848");
```
All is explained in the doc : https://www.starknetjs.com/docs/next/guides/define_call_message#u256
It explains also that if you want to use tokenId to interact with a Cairo 1 contract, you can use directly "1194802964755575003308143629224781921723543461734571264761272012043974606848" as a parameter (not applicable for Cairo 0 contract).

const getLow = number.hexToDecimalString(uint256.bnToUint256(tokenId).low)

```

Author: phil26
Content:
**Cairo v2.0.0** is now deployed in testnet 1/2.
As this new version is implementing a modified format of Abi, Starknet.js v5 is not yet able to handle this new Abi format.
Nevertheless, you can declare/deploy and interact, but only with methods that do not use the abi.
For example, with my test contract : `0x033de869eb1905fe503610527c51e245119bd05c231e7165c95d6fb630fe05ff` in testnet :
```typescript
const res4 = await myTestContract.call("get_counter", [], { parseRequest: false, parseResponse: false });
const txh5 = await myTestContract.invoke("increase_counter", [50], { parseRequest: false, parseResponse: false });
```

Author: phil26
Content:
**Cairo v2.0.0** includes new types : core Enums  and custom Enums.
- Core Enums have only one member today : `Option` (probably also soon `Result` )
- Custom Enum. Example :
Cairo :
```rust
enum MyEnum {
    Response: Order,
    Warning: felt252,
    Error: u16,
}
```
JS :
```typescript
const res6 = await myTestContract.call("test4", [50], { parseRequest: false, parseResponse: false });
    console.log("Result6 =", res6);
    const res7 = await myTestContract.call("test4", [128], { parseRequest: false, parseResponse: false });
    console.log("Result7 =", res7);
```
with response :
```typescript
Result6 = [ '0x1' ]
Result7 = [ '0x0', '0x12', '0x80' ]
```
If you need more information on this subject : https://github.com/0xs34n/starknet.js/issues/669

Author: phil26
Content:
I made some tests : In most cases, it's not working.
I works this way :
```typescript
const u1:Uint256=cairo.uint256(49);
const u2:Uint256=cairo.uint256(50);
type ValsetArgs = {
    validators: BigNumberish[],
    powers: BigNumberish[],
    valsetNonce: Uint256,
}
type RequestPayload ={
    routeAmount: Uint256,
    requestIdentifier: Uint256,
    requestTimestamp: Uint256,
    srcChainId: BigNumberish,
    routeRecipient: BigNumberish,
    destChainId: BigNumberish,
    asmAddress: BigNumberish,
    requestSender: BigNumberish,
    handlerAddress: BigNumberish,
    packet: BigNumberish[],
    isReadCall: boolean,
}
const mySetArgs:ValsetArgs ={
    validators: [234,235],
    powers: [562,567,345],
    valsetNonce: u1,
}
const myRequest:RequestPayload={
    routeAmount: u2,
    requestIdentifier: u1,
    requestTimestamp: u2,
    srcChainId: 100,
    routeRecipient: 101,
    destChainId: 102,
    asmAddress: 103,
    requestSender: 12,
    handlerAddress: 200,
    packet: [13,14,15],
    isReadCall: true,
}
const compiledObj=CallData.compile( {
    currentValset: mySetArgs,
    _sigs: [u1,u2],
    requestPayload: myRequest,
    relayerRouterAddress: 456789,
    });

await myTestContract.iReceive(compiledObj);
```

        '14',  '15',  '1',   '456789'

Author: phil26
Content:
Well, not sure to have understood all.
In summary, you want to do exactly what is doing Starknet.js : prepare and send parameters to a function of a contract.
CallData.compile, myCalldata.compile, myContract.populate are all functions to transform parameters to an array of felts.
myContract.call, .invoke and myAccount.execute are all functions to call a function of a contract, with this felt [].

Author: laoyang33
Content: how to generate unit256 0xffffffffffffffffffffffffffffffffffffffffffffffffffffffffffffffff ?

Author: laoyang33
Content: v4 version

Author: phil26
Content:
You should consider to migrate to V5. V4 will be no more compatible with Starknet.
https://www.starknetjs.com/docs/next/guides/migrate
In V5, it's very easy to generate an Uint256 : 
```typescript
const qty = cairo.uint256("0xffffffffffffffffffffffffffffffffffffffffffffffffffffffffffffffff");
```
And in many cases, it's even no more necessary to convert to Uint256 ; you pass directly the value "0xff...ff".

let c:weierstrass.SignatureType 
```

Author: phil26
Content:
# üì¢ **Starknet.js v5.19.0 is released**
This version is compatible with Cairo-lang 0.12.1 (so with Cairo 2.1.0).
Cairo has introduced new types of data, that are now correctly handled :
- Span : You can send and receive Spans with JS Array type.
- EthAddress : A BigNumberish with 160 bits maxi.
- ContractAddress : A BigNumberish with 251 bits maxi.
- ClassHash : A BigNumberish with 251 bits maxi.
But the most important new type introduced is Enum. 3 types of Enums are valid :
- Option
- Result
- Custom Enum
If a Cairo 2.1.0 function returns a` Result<u8,u16>` with `Result::Ok(200)`, the response in Starknet.js will be an instance of the new `CairoResult` class, for example :
```typescript
const contractResult = await myTestContract.test() as CairoResult<BigNumberish, BigNumberish>;
```
Then you can use this instance in your JS/TS code in a similar way to Cairo :
```typescript
const isSuccess: boolean = contractResult.isOk(); // true
const value: bigint = contractResult.unwrap(); // 200
```
A complete Enums guide has been written here : https://www.starknetjs.com/docs/next/guides/cairo_enum

Author: phil26
Content:
# üì¢  **Starknet.js v5.19.0 use RPC 0.4.0** 
If your DAPP connects to Starknet with a Sequencer, nothing new ; but if you connect with a RPC node, it **MUST** be compatible with RPC 0.4.0.
I checked this afternoon :
- Alchemy : not yet compatible.
- Infura : not yet compatible.
- Devnet 0.6.0a0 : not yet compatible.
The only compatible node is your own local Pathfinder 0.7.0 node, connected to "http://127.0.0.1:9545/rpc/v0.4".
So take care on these points if you use RPC.

Author: phil26
Content:
Hello,
This morning I made several tests. 
**You can follow very closely the status of your transactions just after sending them.**
The code is not exactly the same  for RPC and Sequencer. I made tests with Starknet.js v5.19.0, a Pathfinder v0.7.0 node configured for testnet2 & rpc0.4.0, and the Testnet2 sequencer (Damn, Testnet2 sequencer is so fast this summer Saturday morning!!!).
`myProvider.getTransactionReceipt(txHash)` is a good way to track in real time the status of your transaction.

Author: phil26
Content:
**Track transaction status with Sequencer **
I made a code that scan the status each 250ms.
If the transaction succeed, you have :
```
txH2 = 0x63005d23c9d7a3e3a947afd2fc65aa5b55fa74c8d6f546a55daaeb3b502ff8f
txR: execution = NOT_RECEIVED , NOT_RECEIVED
txR: execution = RECEIVED , RECEIVED
txR: execution = ACCEPTED_ON_L2 , ACCEPTED_ON_L2
txR: execution = ACCEPTED_ON_L2 , ACCEPTED_ON_L2
txR: execution = ACCEPTED_ON_L2 , ACCEPTED_ON_L2
txR: execution = ACCEPTED_ON_L2 , ACCEPTED_ON_L2
txR: execution = ACCEPTED_ON_L2 , ACCEPTED_ON_L2
```
If the transaction fail (for example due to an `assert`):
```
txH2 = 0x6d9e0d031e78ddbb1398d662e226192800e12337bdd56d840da84112ab12457
txR: execution = RECEIVED , RECEIVED
txR: execution = RECEIVED , RECEIVED
txR: execution = REVERTED , ACCEPTED_ON_L2
txR: execution = REVERTED , ACCEPTED_ON_L2
txR: execution = REVERTED , ACCEPTED_ON_L2
txR: execution = REVERTED , ACCEPTED_ON_L2
```

Author: phil26
Content:
**Track transaction status with RPC :**
If the transaction succeed, you have :
```
xH2 = 0x6c04cf323c376dd139c6790e2192e85f9750b6e55feac9ead687d230ad8410b
txR: TxH not yet in memPool.
txR: TxH not yet in memPool.
txR: TxH not yet in memPool.
txR: TxH not yet in memPool.
txR: TxH not yet in memPool.
txR: TxH not yet in memPool.
txR: TxH not yet in memPool.
txR: TxH not yet in memPool.
txR: TxH not yet in memPool.
txR: execution = Succeeded , AcceptedOnL2
txR: execution = Succeeded , AcceptedOnL2
txR: execution = Succeeded , AcceptedOnL2
txR: execution = Succeeded , AcceptedOnL2
```
If the transaction fail :
```
txR: TxH not yet in memPool.
txR: TxH not yet in memPool.
txR: TxH not yet in memPool.
txR: TxH not yet in memPool.
txR: execution = Reverted , AcceptedOnL2
txR: execution = Reverted , AcceptedOnL2
TxR: execution = Reverted , AcceptedOnL2
```

Author: xswagglerx
phil26
Content:
Hello,
Inside Starknet, a Cairo contract can invoke a Cairo function that returns a result.
The Starknet API defines the rules to invoke and call the Cairo functions from outside of Starknet. The API do not authorize to return a result of an invoke.
So, from outside of Starknet, you can solve this problem by :
- Your `create_post` function stores the result in the contract. Then a call function read the storage and returns the result.
- Your `create_post` function  emits the result in an events. Then you can read the event, using the txHash.

Author: phil26
Content:
# **üì¢ Starkware just communicated about the sequencers :**
- Testnet 1&2 sequencers will be definitely stopped end of septembre.
- Mainnet sequencer will be definitely  stopped in octobre.
The only way to communicate with Starknet networks will be with RPC nodes.
So, **DAPP devs have to quickly update their code, to use only RPC provider.**
Starknet.js will soon tag `SequencerProvider` as deprecated, and few time later, will remove it.

Author: phil26
Content:
Hello,
It seems that you have some habits from Ethereum, right?
In opposition to Ethereum, Starknet do not have a hard coded token to pay fees, so there is no "account getBalance".
In Starknet, an ERC 20 contract is managing the fee token, called ETH. So balance of ETH has to be managed as all other ERC20 contracts.
Have a look at my tuto on this subject : https://github.com/PhilippeR26/starknet.js-workshop-typescript/blob/main/proxy.md

Author: kikopashka
Content:
Im sorry, just for be clear

is it mean that erc-20 contract dont know our private key, but he has a signed message by our private key and he can verify that, right ?
Verify without knoweldge of private key

Author: phil26
Content:
Hello,
Absolutely. It's the magic of cryptographic mathematics.
From your private key, you can calculate a public key.
If you sign a message with your private key, you do not reveal this private key.
Then if you send the public key to somebody, he can mathematically verify that the message has been signed with the private key corresponding to the public key in its possession.
https://www.starknetjs.com/docs/next/guides/signature

Author: phil26
Content: As your account stores your public key, it can verify (with this public key) that the transaction that you requested has been signed by yourself (as you are the only one people to have the private key), and not by somebody else who do not hold your private key.

Author: phil26
Content: So, in fact, the initial check is made in your account, not in the ERC20.

Author: phil26
Content:
Seems to be a little the mess to use the rpc nodes with the migration to rpc 0.4.0.
Taking into account the status made this morning, here are my recommendations :
Use Starknet.js v5.19.5, with :
- local : Pathfinder with `/rpc/v0.4` at the end of the address.
- remote : use infura
- remote : Blast.io : use  `"https://starknet-testnet.blastapi.io/" + blastKey +"/rpc/v0.4"`

Alchemy is generating responses without status and shall be avoided until they upgrade their node.

The problem is that it's recorded in the blockchain once the pending block is validated.
From Cairo-lang v0.12.1, we have some problems to use the nonce. If you send a quick burst of transactions, you can have a problem of nonce.

Content: is there function or method to do sha256 hash from string ?

Author: phil26
Content:
Zk proof provers do not like sha256 hash. They prefer Pedersen or Poseidon hashes.
That's why there is no such hash in Starknet.js.
But if you want absolutely to use it, a very good library is here : https://github.com/paulmillr/noble-hashes

Author: phil26
Content:
Hello,
1. Use `account.execute()`, to perform all transactions with the same nonce.
2. Normally, use` waitForTransaction` between each transaction is enough : https://www.starknetjs.com/docs/next/guides/interact/#sending-sequential-transactions
3. wait until the pending block is validated, before next tx.

Author: aaron_tea
Content: What happens to my account when I update my wallet?

Author: phil26
Content: Which wallet are you using?

Author: aaron_tea
Content: ArgentX

Author: phil26
Content:
If you perform a call of the proxy function `get_implementation()` before the update, you will obtain the class hash of the current code used in this account. When you update your account, the wallet launch the function `upgrade(implementation, constructor)`, that will change the class applicable for this account.
If you perform again a call to `get_implementation()`, you will see that the class hash has changed.
So, when Argent is asking you to accept an update, it means that you accept that the code of your account will be changed. You have to believe that this new code will not jeopardize your assets.

Author: aaron_tea
Content: What if I use an OpenZeppelin account

Author: phil26
Content:
As there is no proxy with OpenZeppelin, this account is really trust-less. No risk of hazardous update code ; no needs to thrust somebody. Nevertheless, it means that the account code is definitely frozen.
So, impossible to update an OpenZeppelin account.

Author: phil26
Content:
Hello,
An account contract contains a \_\_execute\_\_ function, to ... execute your transaction. The way it handles its inputs is not the same in Cairo 1 and in Cairo 0. So, Starknet.js  must be informed of the language of the account, to organize the data the appropriate way.

Author: phil26
Content: Today, it's by default Cairo 0, but if you put "1" as last parameter of Account instance creation, you ask to Starknet.js to adapt data to a Cairo 1 account.

Author: phil26
Content:
## üì¢  Soon Cairo 1 will become the default type of account
So, "1" will no more be necessary for Cairo 1 accounts,
but "0" will become mandatory for Cairo 0 accounts.
# **My recommendation is to always implement this parameter. **
Documentation will be updated soon in this way.
```typescript
const accountOZ060 = new Account(provider, accountAddress, privateKey, "0"); // for Cairo 0 account
const accountAX030 = new Account(provider, accountAddress, privateKey, "1"); // for Cairo 1 account
```

Author: vlasovviach
Content:
`Sequencer simulate process only first element from invocations list`
Why is that happening while simulateTransaction call? How do I simulate all the calls but not only first?
Don't tell me I need to loop through them all lol

Author: phil26
Content:
Hello,
To limit the CPU usage of the sequencer, it accepts only the first Invoke.
Try with a connection to a Node.
Take care that the rpc specification 0.4.0 ask to the "multiCall simulate" to answer for all accepted transactions before any reverted Invoke, and an explanation for the first reverted Invoke. Unfortunately, Nodes team have not followed this rule, and in case of one Invoke reverted, most of them are Reverting all the request without any explanation....

Author: phil26
Content:
You can only use String or BigInt (that do not accept decimals).
With String, if you want to convert wei to ETH, you can use :
```typescript
const amount=123_900_000_000_000_000_000n; //123.9 ETH
const amountStr=amount.toString();
console.log(amountStr.slice(0,-18)+"."+amountStr.slice(-18));
```

Author: doc_product
Content:
Alchemy does. Infura does not.

In terms of the underlying full node implementations, both Pathfinder and Juno support websockets now. So it's up to the RPC providers to turn it on.

(Plug: At Nethermind we're working on our RPC service and we already support websockets. Will launch soon.)

Doesn't look like there's any support in either `starknet.js` or `starknet-rs` yet though which is a bummer.
